<br>
The easiest fusion reactions, in terms of energy cross sections, are, going from lowest up, <br>
<br>
A) deuterium and tritium  (DT)<br>
B) deuterium and deuterium (DD)<br>
C) Deuterium and helium3  (DH3)<br>
<br>
The reason they rank this way makes my head hurt, so I will let you figure it out if you want.<br>
<br>
Let's look at all three of these, shall we?  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
DT is EASY to make happen, but the energy that comes out is hard to use.  D has a nucleus consisting of a proton and a neutron, while T has a nucleus of a proton and two neutrons.  Fusing these together means you have 2 protons and 3 neutrons.  Normal helium has 2 protons and 2 neutrons, so the extra neutron gets tossed out by the extra energy liberated by the fusion action.  <br>
<br>
The trouble is, neutrons are NEUTRAL in charge.  They zip right past the negatively charged electron shells of most atoms until they happen to smash into a nucleus somewhere and eventually slow down enough to get captured.  In other words, neutrons are very PENETRATING, and DT produces most of its power from fast neutrons.  It is hard to turn DT output into useful power.<br>
<br>
Now, DH3 is somewhat harder to cause than DT, but the energy is WAY easier to use.  Why?  Well, D as I said has 1 proton and 1 neutron, but H3 has 2 PROTONS and 1 NEUTRON.  Or, a total after they get fused together of 3 protons and 2 neutrons.  Well, since H4 has 2 and 2, the extra particle again gets tossed out, but in this case it is a proton.  <br>
<br>
Protons have a positive charge, which means they have a tremendously hard time making their way through the negatively charged electron shells of normal matter.  Or, they do NOT penetrate, and quickly dump their energy as heat in almost any medium.<br>
<br>
So, in theory, a mass fusion rocket using DH3 as fuel would produce an exhaust of almost pure H4 helium and bucket loads of heat and protons.   You would not want to go stand in the way of the exhaust, but the same can be said for ANY current rocket exhaust.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   It is NOT lethal poison by any stretch of the imagination.<br>
<br>
The real problem lies in the fact that the closest supply of H3 is on the Moon....   <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
